<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910508-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910508-0114.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   Endangered Economics</HL><DATE>05/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>INTERIOR DEPARTMENT (INR)</GV><LP>   Environmental groups keep telling us they really do careabout economics. And we keep looking for any sustainedevidence this is true. Now along comes a story yesterday thatenvironmentalists, notably the National Wildlife Federation,are upset about an Interior Department memo saying thegovernment will consider both economics and biology insolving the Northwest spotted-owl controversy. That, says thefederation, is &quot;illegal&quot;; the Endangered Species Act permitsplanning based only on scientific considerations. Theimplication, as we've repeatedly said, is that matters ofcost receive little, if any, priority in the philosophy orstrategies of too many environmental groups.</LP><TEXT/></DOC>